## General Objectives

- Keep code readable, testable, and easy to scale by feature.
- Prefer small, scoped changes; avoid broad refactors unless explicitly requested.

## Stack and Coding Standards

- Vue 3 + Composition API + `<script setup lang="ts">` is the default.
- Avoid `any`; if unavoidable, limit scope and document why.
- Default file naming is `kebab-case`; keep upstream exceptions in `src/components/ui/**`.

## Required Folder Structure

- `src/pages/`: route-level pages and feature-local components.
- `src/components/ui/`: reusable UI primitives (shadcn-vue).
- `src/components/`: shared components used across features.
- `src/composables/`: reusable logic (`use-*.ts`).
- `src/stores/`: shared/global Pinia state.
- `src/services/api/`: query/mutation hooks and API access.
- `src/services/types/`: shared service/data contract types.
- `src/plugins/`: i18n, pinia, query, router, etc.

## Architecture and Dependency Direction

- Preferred flow: `pages -> components/composables -> services -> types/utils`.
- Lower layers must not import higher layers.
- Do not place heavy business logic inside `.vue` pages/components; move it to composables/services/stores.
- Avoid god files; split modules when components become too large or multi-purpose.

## Service API / Data Contracts

- Do not call HTTP directly in pages/components when a service hook exists.
- Query keys must be stable arrays, domain-first (e.g., `['tasks']`, `['task', id]`).
- Mutations must invalidate related queries in `onSuccess`/`onSettled`.
- Keep DTO and UI/domain models distinct; normalize/map API data in the service layer.
- Do not pass raw API shapes directly to UI when normalization/null-safety is needed.

## Pinia / Router / Composables

- Use Pinia for shared state only; keep local UI state in components/composables.
- Avoid direct store-state destructuring that breaks reactivity; prefer `storeToRefs`.
- Router guards must handle async flows clearly and avoid redirect loops/race conditions.
- For same-component route changes (`params/query`), handle updates with proper watch/logic (do not assume remount).
- Each composable should have one clear purpose with typed inputs/outputs; avoid hidden singletons.

## Component Conventions (Atomic + Feature Boundaries)

- Do not place single-feature components in shared folders.
- Shared components must not import from feature folders.
- Do not violate hierarchy with cross-level reverse imports.
- Avoid over-generalized components with excessive props; split into focused variants.
- Prefer composition/slots over complex boolean-prop APIs.
- If a higher-level reusable pattern already exists (molecule/organism), reuse it instead of hand-composing atoms.
- Molecules must not fetch data; data fetching belongs in organisms or feature components.

## Tailwind / UI / Motion

- Prefer mobile-first, token-based styling with intentional classes; avoid unmaintainable class strings.
- Theme/token updates must remain compatible with the project’s Tailwind version.
- Use animation intentionally and sparingly; respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- If the prompt asks to create/update UI (layout, style, spacing, typography, interaction, animation, accessibility), apply `ui-ux-pro-max` before coding.
- If the task is non-UI (API, DB, infra, scripts), do not use `ui-ux-pro-max`.
- Use `ui-ux-pro-max` only for UI/UX decisions; it does not replace architecture, data-layer, or quality-gate rules.

## Error Handling and Observability

- No empty `catch {}` blocks.
- All important async flows must expose clear `loading/success/error` states.
- Do not display raw server errors directly to end users.
- Retry only transient failures, with bounded attempts and basic backoff.

## Quality Gates Before Handoff

- Do not add dead code or unnecessary TODO comments.
- Keep internal contracts stable (props/emits/store/API); when contracts change, update related call sites.
- Run lint/typecheck for changed scope and fix newly introduced issues.
- For non-obvious technical decisions, add a brief code note or task/PR explanation.
